-- Populate ideal_answer JSONB for 2 design questions

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "Design a multi-layer trust & safety system for Alexa+ LLM responses: safety taxonomy, real-time filtering, LLM-as-judge evaluation, and continuous drift monitoring.", "outline": ["Clarify scope: response types (factual, creative, task completion), user demographics (children vs adults), risk categories", "Safety taxonomy: harmful content, misinformation, PII leakage, bias, regulatory non-compliance", "Architecture: 3-layer pipeline — rule-based blocklist (microseconds), ML classifier (milliseconds), LLM safety judge (100ms)", "Evaluation: offline test suites per risk category, adversarial red-teaming, production monitoring with drift detection", "Scale considerations: pre-computed safety scores for common responses, streaming evaluation for novel outputs"], "full_response": "I would start by clarifying scope and constraints. What types of Alexa+ responses are we evaluating — factual answers, creative generation, task completion, multi-turn conversation? What''s the user demographic mix — the system must be significantly stricter for children''s interactions. What are the latency requirements — can safety evaluation add 200ms to response time, or must it be near-zero? What regulatory frameworks apply (COPPA for children, EU AI Act, FTC guidelines)?\n\nThe safety taxonomy defines what we''re detecting. I''d structure it as: Tier 1 (block immediately) — explicit harmful content, instructions for dangerous activities, PII exposure, CSAM. Tier 2 (flag for review) — medical/legal advice that could cause harm, culturally sensitive content, potential misinformation on high-stakes topics. Tier 3 (monitor and learn) — bias patterns, subtle stereotyping, quality degradation, off-topic responses.\n\nThe architecture is a three-layer pipeline, similar to what I built for content safety at Walmart but adapted for real-time conversational AI. Layer 1: rule-based filters run in microseconds — blocklists, regex patterns for PII (SSN, credit card numbers), and hard blocks on known dangerous query-response patterns. This catches the easy cases with near-zero latency. Layer 2: a lightweight ML classifier (distilled BERT or similar) trained on human-labeled safety data, running in 10-20ms. It outputs a safety probability per risk category. Layer 3: an LLM safety judge with a structured rubric, reserved for the ambiguous zone between Layer 2''s auto-pass and auto-block thresholds. The judge evaluates nuance — is this medical information dangerous or helpful? Is this political content biased or balanced?\n\nThe key design choice is whether safety evaluation runs pre-generation (filtering the LLM''s output tokens as they''re generated) or post-generation (evaluating the complete response). Pre-generation allows early stopping but requires streaming evaluation; post-generation is simpler but adds latency. I''d propose a hybrid: Layer 1 runs as a streaming filter on output tokens, Layer 2 evaluates the complete response before delivery, and Layer 3 runs asynchronously with results used for monitoring and model improvement rather than blocking.\n\nFor evaluation, I''d build offline test suites with known-unsafe and known-safe examples per risk category, adversarial red-teaming sets designed to bypass each layer, and production monitoring dashboards tracking safety flag rates, false positive rates (safe content blocked), and drift in safety score distributions. The drift monitoring is critical — as the underlying Alexa+ LLM is updated, its failure modes change, and the safety system must adapt.\n\nScale considerations: for common queries, pre-compute safety evaluations and cache them. For novel or long-tail queries, the full pipeline runs. The LLM judge (Layer 3) is the cost bottleneck — manage it by only routing ambiguous cases there (2-5% of traffic based on my experience at Walmart)."}'::jsonb WHERE id = 'c7443b08-7a93-400f-a47e-a386f2995fe1';

UPDATE onsite_prep_questions SET ideal_answer = '{"summary": "Design a personalized video discovery system: two-tower retrieval, cross-encoder ranking, multi-objective optimization balancing engagement, diversity, and freshness.", "outline": ["Clarify: discovery surfaces (homepage, search, post-play), success metrics (watch-through rate, session length, subscription retention)", "Candidate generation: two-tower model with user behavior sequence + content embeddings, FAISS ANN index", "Ranking: cross-encoder with features from watch history, content metadata, context (time, device), social signals", "Multi-objective: balance engagement (watch-through) with diversity (genre coverage) and freshness (new content promotion)", "Cold-start: content-based embeddings for new titles, explore-exploit for new users, multi-armed bandit for UI experiments"], "full_response": "I''d start by clarifying the discovery surfaces and success metrics. Are we optimizing homepage recommendations, search results, post-play suggestions, or all three? Each has different signals and constraints. The primary metric should be watch-through rate (fraction of video actually watched) rather than click-through rate — clicks are cheap, but sustained viewing indicates genuine value. Secondary metrics: session length, cross-genre exploration rate, and subscription retention as the ultimate north star.\n\nCandidate generation uses a two-tower architecture. The user tower encodes the user''s watch history as a sequence (recent titles, genres, actors, watch completion rates), plus demographic features and context (time of day, device type, day of week). The content tower encodes video metadata: genre, cast, director, release date, synopsis embedding, visual style embedding from trailer/poster, and engagement statistics. Both towers map to a shared 128-dimensional space trained with InfoNCE loss on (user, watched_video) positive pairs.\n\nThe content embedding strategy deserves special attention for video. Unlike e-commerce where item attributes are mostly text, video content has rich multimodal signals. I''d use a pre-trained vision-language model (CLIP or similar) to encode trailer keyframes and poster images, concatenated with text embeddings of the synopsis and metadata. This multimodal embedding captures visual style, which is a strong signal for user preference that text alone misses.\n\nThe ranking stage takes the top-500 candidates from retrieval and applies a cross-encoder model that jointly processes user context and video features. The ranking model''s features include: retrieval score, content-based similarity to recent watches, temporal features (how long since the user last watched this genre), social signals (trending in the user''s demographic), and business signals (Prime Original boost, licensing window urgency).\n\nMulti-objective optimization is critical for video discovery because pure engagement optimization creates filter bubbles — users get stuck in one genre. I''d use a scalarized multi-objective approach: final_score = w1 * engagement_score + w2 * diversity_bonus + w3 * freshness_bonus + w4 * explore_bonus. The diversity bonus rewards recommending genres the user hasn''t watched recently. The freshness bonus promotes recently released content. The explore bonus is a Thompson sampling-based signal that promotes content the system is uncertain about for the user. The weights are tuned via online experiments.\n\nCold-start for new titles: the content tower produces embeddings from metadata alone (synopsis, cast, genre, trailer visuals). For the first 2 weeks after release, the title gets an exploration boost that decays as engagement data accumulates. New users start with popularity-based recommendations segmented by acquisition channel (a user who signed up for a specific show gets different initial recommendations than one who came from a generic ad), transitioning to personalized recommendations after 5-10 viewing sessions.\n\nServing architecture: FAISS index updated hourly for candidate generation, ranking model served via a GPU inference service with <100ms p99 latency, results cached per user with a 1-hour TTL that''s invalidated on new watch events."}'::jsonb WHERE id = '8eb8092d-e771-4dea-a93b-1a5c6c87f7ae';
